article.description: Agnieszka Bibrzycka was at her best with the game on the line.
article.headline: Johnson notches 13 points, 10 assists
article.linkText: Mercury fall short to Silver Stars in overtime
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Agnieszka Bibrzycka was at her best with the game
on the line.

The Polish rookie made a 3-pointer early in overtime, giving the
San Antonio Silver Stars a five-point lead en route to an 80-72
victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Saturday night.

The Silver Stars (5-9) won their second straight game. On
Thursday night, they snapped a franchise-record eight-game losing
streak with a victory over Minnesota.

LaToya Thomas scored 14 points, Shannon Johnson had 13 points
and 10 assists, and Margo Dydek added 10 points and 11 rebounds for
the Silver Stars. Bibrzycka, who entered the game with a 2.1
scoring average, finished with eight.

"The league is so talented," Johnson said. "Before, you could
go out and score as many points as you wanted and you won. Now, you
have to be able to play team basketball."

Bibrzycka's 3-pointer with 1:11 left in regulation gave the
Silver Stars a 62-58 lead.

The Mercury (6-6) fought back, holding San Antonio to four free
throws the rest of the way, and tied it at 66 on Anna DeForge's
three free throws with 35.8 seconds left and a 3-pointer by Penny
Taylor with 4.7 seconds to go.

"At the end, Penny hit a huge shot, forced it to overtime,"
Phoenix rookie Diana Taurasi said. "And in overtime we just, you
know, offensively I don't think we executed very well."

Johnson made a layup 1:14 into the extra period, and the Stars
took a 71-66 lead on Bibrzycka's second 3-pointer with 3:04 left.

"We gave them a chance to get back in the game, and that was a
disappointment," Stars coach Dee Brown said.

Taylor had a season-high 25 points for Phoenix, Taurasi added 17
and Anna DeForge had 11. Taurasi was 8-for-24 from the field, but
made her only two shots in overtime.

"I think we showed character to get ourselves back in the
game," Mercury coach Carrie Graf said. "We put ourselves in a
hole, because we didn't contain the ball early on."
